      "content": "Proponents frequently utilized a theoretical framework suggesting that cultural integration would inevitably lead to social friction and the dilution of core community values. They argued that maintaining separate social ecosystems allowed each group to develop and practice its distinct cultural norms without interference, thereby preventing the competition for resources they believed would arise from mixing. This perspective posited that segregation acted as a prophylactic measure against the instability, crime, and social unrest they feared would result from rapid demographic transition.",
